			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">&quot;The significant AND ONLY difference between 240p and 480i:<br /><br />&quot;They are identical in every way, except that the second field of 480i is delayed by 1/2 horizontal line!<br /><br />THAT and only *THAT* is what makes it *Interlaced*.<br /><br />For both 240P and 480i the H and V frequencies are identical: 15750 for H and 60 for V. By delaying the second field [all 262.5 of the even numbered lines] in 480i by 1/2 H line, thevideo is then interlaced. By the way, this has to happen at the videosource and can't be changed in an NTSC *ONLY* TV.<br /><br />There is nothing in a standard NTSC &quot;15KHZ&quot; TV set, not the CRT, not the video amp circuitry, or anything else that can change a non-interlaced 240p progressive scanned incoming signal into an interlaced signal and display it as an interlaced image&quot;<br /><br />After reading this, i decided to post this here, i know i must sound like a noob, but is there not something i could do on the xbox with this? instead of messing with registers and encoders? makes it sound so easy.  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_mrgreen.gif" alt=":mrgreen:" title="Mr. Green" />  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_evil.gif" alt=":evil:" title="Evil or Very Mad" /></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
