						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://forums.shoryuken.com/discussion/comment/7999216/#Comment_7999216" class="postlink">someone</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">For both 240P and 480i the H and V frequencies are identical: 15750 for H and 60 for V. By delaying the second field [all 262.5 of the even numbered lines] in 480i by 1/2 H line, thevideo is then interlaced.<br /></div>That's ... not true.<br />First:<br />RS170 is 15750 Hz horizontal, 60 Hz vertical, interlaced. (15750 Ã· 60 = 262.5) But it's monochrome.<br />NTSC (what most people mean when they say 480i) is 15734 Hz horizontal, 59.94 vertical, interlaced. (15734 Ã· 59.94 = 262.5 ; 15734 = 3579545 Ã· 227.5)<br />It is the non-integer ratio between the hsync and vsync rates that specifically causes interlaced behavior; the same is true for the old 1024x768@86i (ratio of 408.5) or the newer 1080i (ratio of 562.5).<br />240p is a clever abuse of NTSC, never intended. It horizontal to vertical ratio is either 262 or 263 scanlines depending on implementation. This would be equivalent to 480i with 524 or 526 scanlines per two fields. As such, the refresh rate will be slightly faster or slightly slower than 59.94 Hz.<br /><br />Most televisions will deal fine with signals that vary up to 1% from the nominal hsync rate and up to 5% from the nominal vsync rate. Some ( especially PAL sets) support all the way from 15625-1% to 15750+1% hsync and 47-63 Hz vsync.<br /><div class="quotetitle">*Spitfire_NES* wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">After reading this, i decided to post this here, i know i must sound like a noob, but is there not something i could do on the xbox with this? instead of messing with registers and encoders? makes it sound so easy.<br /></div>Unfortunately, what he's describing (&quot;failing to delay the second field by half a scanline&quot;) is exactly what reprogramming the conexant IC does.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

