				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Some new information has come to light regarding this possibility and figured i would post this here: <br /><br />this is taken from the xdk doc for xbox:<br /><br /><span style="color: #FF4000">[color=#BF0000]FieldRender Sample<br />The FieldRender sample shows how to do field rendering. Normally, Xbox games render to one 640Ã—480 buffer at 60 Hz, and the hardware filters the buffer down to odd and even interlaced fields. With field rendering, a game renders separately for the odd and even fields, and only to a 640Ã—240 buffer.<br /><br />Field rendering saves on fill rate (since only half as many pixels are drawn), but the resulting quality is not as good.<br /><br />Field rendering is enabled during device creation by using the D3DPRESENTFLAG_FIELD flag. The title must render at 60 fps for field rendering. To minimize flicker, the viewport must be offset by one scan line during the rendering of even fields. Finally, note that the flicker filter does not work when field rendering is enabled.</span><br /><br /><span style="color: #FF4000">[color=#FF4000]Field rendering<br /><br />Field rendering is a special video mode where the back buffer size is assumed to be half the vertical height of the output display and the output format is defined to be interlaced. In this mode, the even lines of the display are rendered during one field and the odd lines are rendered during the next field. When using field rendering, the flicker filter is disabled. Field rendering can reduce the fill-rate and bandwidth requirements of a game substantially; however, since there is no flicker filter, display quality can also be somewhat degraded.<br /><br />Field rendering is supported with all AV packs.<br /><br />This video mode is enabled by specifying D3DPRESENTFLAG_FIELD as one of the flags ORed into the Flags member of D3DPRESENT_PARAMETERS.<br /><br />To minimize flickering, a screen offset needs to be applied during the rendering of even fields. IDirect3DDevice8::GetDisplayFieldStatus can be used to determine if the field is even or odd. Before rendering the even fields, the title should apply an offset of (0.0f, 0.5f) using IDirect3DDevice8::SetScreenSpaceOffset.</span><br /><br />Could this not be the information to make the xbox display only one field in 480i effectively 240p?</div>

